40|$|This paper {{examines}} {{the relationship between}} manufacturing exports and <b>imports</b> <b>of</b> <b>capital</b> goods in Thailand using monthly data from January 2000 to July 2011. The results from bounds testing for cointegration show that there exists long-run equilibrium relationship between exports and <b>imports</b> <b>of</b> <b>capital</b> goods in manufacturing sector. In addition, the positive relationship between the growth rate <b>of</b> <b>imports</b> <b>of</b> <b>capital</b> goods and {{the growth rate of}} manufacturing exports is observed. The results support the notion that foreign capital is essential in the process of industrialization, and thus economic growth. A decline in <b>imports</b> <b>of</b> <b>capital</b> goods will reduce manufacturing exports and impedes economic growth in the future. It is also likely that exports of manufactured products are the main source of foreign exchanges to finance <b>imports</b> <b>of</b> <b>capital</b> goods which cannot be produced in the country due to comparative disadvantage. ...|$|R
